recording.type: song, Likely an immature practice bower, with immature practice song
recording.rmk:
microphones placed 10cm above ground on vines, 20cm apart, 40 cm from the bower. This was a subadult male (similar plumage to female but yellow bill), female at times in attendance. Bower was decorated with macadamia nut shells and green leaves and shells were held up in presentation to female. A dance of sorts was performed with spread wings and bobbing. Female entered at the opposite end of the bower avenue. Bower located under clump of lantana vine in a degraded regrowth remnant corridor (mixed rainforest and weed species ) 20 metres wide and 500metres long, between 2 macadamia nut orchards and quite close to a road. Low cut filters used to reduce traffic and farm machinery noise. Bird returned regularly to the bower throughout the day. 
PS: Subsequent observation of this bower over several days, revealed that only immature birds and subadult males attended, at least 3 different individuals and no adult males seen: this is likely a “practice bower” built by young birds (as seen in Satin Bowerbirds) and used singly or in groups to practice bower building and performance/decoration including dance display and song. Vocalisations were extremely low levels as if signalling to the bird itself or an immediately adjacent partner in or near the bower.
This was a continuous recording, no edits.

recording.rmk:
A group of five Royal Spoonbills, alongside a group of twelve pelicans, and a group of nine Silver Gulls, standing in shallow water of the Coorong at Long Point. The other four Royal Spoonbills remained silent. All were foraging for food with their bills in the shallow water. From a distance, at first I assumed that this vocal bird, although similar in appearance, might be of a different species, given that its behaviour and bodily postures seemed so different from those of the other four Spoonbills. power_text: When another player takes the "lay eggs" action, lay 1 [egg] on a bird with a [bowl] nest.
note:
These birds are all nest parasites in the wild: they lay eggs in other birds’ nests. Cowbirds don’t even build their own nests.
When another player uses the [grassland] action to lay eggs, you may lay 1 egg. You may do this only once between your turns, no matter how many other players lay eggs. The cowbird can lay eggs on star nests.

rulings.text: You may not use this bird's power to lay an [egg] on another player's bird.

additionalrulings.text: You may use a pink power during another player's turn after your last turn of the game.
You may activate each "once between turns" power on a bird on your player mat once between each of your turns.
You may not use a pink power during your turn (when an opponent performs an action that would otherwise enable using such a power).

If a pink power is triggered by a player using the "gain food", "lay eggs", or "draw bird cards" action, the pink power is resolved after the player collects the resources indicated on the player mat but before any brown powers in the corresponding row are activated. If a pink power is triggered by another bird's power, the pink power is resolved after the other bird's power has been resolved.
Whenever you are entitled to gain resources, you may choose to take some but not all of the quantity specified.

power_text: If this bird is to the right of all other birds in its habitat, move it to another habitat.
note: These birds are all able to live in a variety of habitats, and their power is to move from habitat to habitat—but only if they’re the last bird in that row. (They can be in any column.) This can be powerful for increasing your abilities in multiple habitats, and for scoring on end-of-round goals. Be careful not to play another bird to the right of one of these cards, or you won’t be able to use its power!

rulings.text: When using this bird's power to move this bird to another habitat, the action cube does not change habitats with it.

recording.rmk:
I am nearly certain that this is the call of a Yellow-breasted Chat, although one previously unknown to me. I did not actually see the chat open its beak, and make these sounds. But the sound was coming from the immediate vicinity of a chat. I initially wondered if this could be the call of a Curve-billed Thrasher. Another birder pointed out to me that the Wood Thrush has a similar call. And I note that the flight call of the Upland Sandpiper is similar. Anyhow, I believe this is a Yellow-breasted Chat.

EDIT: The bird was subsequently SEEN giving this vocalization. In fact, a chat ("the" chat?) gave this same vocalization at this location in the following summer. --Ted Floyd
